General.DocTitle: Rivals cut from the same cloth

headline.p: Rivals cut from the same cloth

headline-web.p: Rudd, Abott like blueprint copies, united by self-belief, relentless persistence and killer instinct

standfirst.p: Columnist Susan Mitchell finds spooky similarities between the leaders that go deeper than surface differences

text.p: At the time of writing this, I do not know who will be our new prime Minister. But throughout the recent election campaign, I was bothered by a strange and rather spooky feeling that the two leaders from opposing parties were not opposites but actually blueprint copies of each other. Replicants, almost.

Yes, I know we are talking about two men who look nothing alike and in terms of ideology are direct opposites. The nerd and the pugilist. The swat and the bovver-boy. But these are only surface differences. What unites them is their motivation.

When Tony Abbott started school he wore glasses and spoke with a pommy accent. Determined to fit in, he quickly discarded the glasses, changed his accent and reinvented himself as a typical Aussie boy. Behind the jokey, boyo manner and the obsession with sport was, however, someone who was determined to be a winner. His parents, particularly his mother, believed that he was special and that he would either become the pope or the prime minister. He shared her sense of destiny. At Riverview, a prestigious Catholic college on Sydney’s affluent north shore many of his schoolmates found him arrogant and “full of himself”. The one thing that really upset him was that no matter how hard he trained, he only ever made the second team in rugby and rowing. He hated coming second in anything.

Kevin Rudd was born in the same year as Tony Abbott. He grew up on a dairy farm on the Sunshine Coast in Queensland. When he was 11, his father died and three weeks later his family was asked to leave the farm. After running out of relatives, Rudd remembers the family being forced to sleep in the car. The shame and the injustice of this etched itself into Rudd’s psyche. He swore to himself that he would never be made to feel like this again. Nor should any other Australian family. He became “a charity case” at the Marist College in Brisbane which he described as “tough, harsh and unforgiving.” Two years later when his mother had retrained as a nurse she moved the family back to the Sunshine Coast where Rudd was coldly determined to reinvent himself through study and scholastic success. In 1974 he was dux of Nambour State High School.
Tony Abbott meanwhile had become the acolyte of Father Costello, a rich Jesuit at Riverview, well-connected with conservatives. He encouraged the young Abbott to consider a career in politics.

Abbott’s first choice was to become a Catholic priest, Rudd’s to become a diplomat. But both of them wanted to achieve something much bigger. Neither had progressed through the usual party machines but both managed to become preselected and elected to federal parliament. Neither of them ever took their eyes off gaining the top job.

Rudd gained it first by defeating Abbott’s political hero and mentor John Howard in 2007. This shattered Abbott but he pulled himself together and kept his eyes on the prize. Malcolm Turnbull was his major obstacle but when he joined with Rudd by nailing his colours to an ETS, Abbott stepped in and split the party, winning the leadership by one vote. He rallied his troops with military expressions like, “train your fire on the other side. Never, ever give up.”

With fierce determination Abbott took on Rudd, both of them convinced that nothing would prevent them from succeeding. In 2010, after Rudd’s decision to delay the introduction of an ETS, his ratings began to drop inside and outside the party. The powerbrokers in the ALP gathered the numbers and made the decision to replace him as PM with Julia Gillard. Not since he had been forced to sleep in the family car as a young boy had Rudd felt so discarded and humiliated. He believed a great injustice had been done to him and he spent the next three years determined to reinstate himself. Nothing and no one was going to stop him.
Meanwhile, Abbott was totally convinced that he would win the 2010 election and he put every ounce of energy and employed every devious tactic to ensure his success.
When the Independents in the hung parliament chose Julia Gillard and not him to form the government, he was apoplectic with rage at coming second.
Gillard now had both Rudd and Abbott determined to destroy her. Rudd finally succeeded in regaining what he considered was rightly his and the battle between the two men resumed.

Both were outsiders who came to politics after another profession. Both relied totally on their powers of persuasion and cunning to rise through the ranks to the position of leader. Both had a sense of destiny. Both were determined that no one would prevent them from rising to the top. Both were prepared to do whatever it took to get there. Both were committed Christians. Both fancied themselves as writers and thinkers. Both have a relentless persistence, a killer instinct and an ego bordering on narcissism that no one but the other could destroy.
For them both, this political aphorism will be true.
“In victory, revenge.
In defeat, malice.”
susanmitchell.com.au

p.s1: LEFT: Schoolboy Kevin Rudd with his older brother Greg in an undated family photograph from their Sunshine Coast childhood.
ABOVE: Tony Abbott with his parents on his graduation from Sydney University. They always believed he was destined for great things.
